grid

Class Grid<T extends Tile>

  • java.lang.Object
    • grid.Grid<T>
  • Type Parameters:
    T - - The type of elements to store.
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.lang.Cloneable, java.lang.Iterable<T>, java.util.Collection<T>
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    Matrix

    public class Grid<T extends Tile>
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.util.Collection<T>, java.lang.Cloneable
    A collection for arbitrarily deep nested arrays Allows for the creation of variable-depth (determined at runtime) matrices. Elements in a grid must extend tile, which allows an element to know its location (treated like a hashcode). A grid is treated as an array, meaning that get and set (and similar) operations may throw an ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException if the listed location is outside the bounds of the grid
    Author:
    Mshnik

      • merge

        public static <T extends Tile> Grid<T> merge(Grid<? extends T> grid1,
                                             Grid<? extends T> grid2,
                                             java.util.function.BinaryOperator<T> combinor)
                                      throws grid.Grid.IllegalDimensionException
        Returns a new grid that is the merged version of the two input grids (which must be of the same dimension)
        Parameters:
        grid1 - - the first grid to merge
        grid2 - - the second grid to merge
        combinor - - a functional interface describing how to combine two tiles into one. The first argument to combine will be a tile from grid1, and the second will be a tile from grid2.
        Returns:
        - A grid with array size equal to the max of the two grids on each dimension, and each element combined
        Throws:
        grid.Grid.IllegalDimensionException
